<Author>justposting
<Content>Very disappointing! I have never written any online review, but I feel compelled to post regarding the Wyndham Bourbon Orleans. I stayed from Thursday through Sunday with my husband, 2 children and our niece. Before making reservations, I viewed a picture of one of the townhouse suites online on their website. (I don't think the photo is there anymore) It looked roomy and nice. The plan was to have the children sleep on the sofa bed and a roll-away bed for our niece. Here is a breakdown of our first and last visit to the Bourbon Orleans:Day One: After loading the luggage onto the cart at check-in , the bellhop walked off, leaving us to get the luggage to the room ourselves. Not a real big deal, but inconvenient when you're carrying tired children. When we got to our room, we were disappointed to see that the suite was actually very small. The smell was unpleasant. The carpet was stained and dirty. The sofa was very uncomfortable (hard as a rock) and the seat cushions would sink down into the frame after you sat for a bit. When we pulled out the sofa bed, we were disappointed to find that the metal coils that connect the under layer to the frame were uncoiled and disconnected, resulting in the mattress falling through the frame. There were also no linens or pillows for the sofa bed, so we attempted to call the front desk to have them repair it and bring linens. The phone did not work. We went down and made the request. After 30 minutes, a maintenance person appeared and tried to repair the sofa bed. He seemed bothered and gave up after a few minutes, saying he didn't know if he could fix it. My husband ended up fixing it. The maintenance person appeared relieved and was happy to meet our simpler request of taking a look at the non-working phone. The linens were brought up 45 minutes after the initial request and consisted of 2 lumpy, pathetic pillows and three flat sheets. We had to go back down to request a blanket. When it came it had several spots of dried crusty something-or-other on it. We put it in the closet and improvised with linens from the larger bed. Day Two: Breakfast food at the hotel was decent but pricey. The thing that really got me was the attitude of the staff. They were rude! And although there was hardly a patron having breakfast there, the wait to be seated sign was out. So we waited several minutes. Finally a staff member who had been watching us wait to be seated came over and motioned us in to sit anywhere. At the end of the meal I attempted to hand the waitress our payment as she strolled by. She rolled her eyes at me and walked off without a word! A couple of minutes later, another staffer took the payment. Later that day we returned from an afternoon of sightseeing to find housekeeping in our room. She told us we were to wait outside 15 more minutes while she finished up. We were tired, and hanging out for fifteen minutes somewhere in the hotel for her convenience did not suit me. We came in and politely told her we would stay downstairs out of her way since the upstairs was what she had to finish. She made this really annoyed face and muttered [--] when she turned around. That was the last time someone from housekeeping entered our suite the rest of our stay. They simply did not come back. For towels, we helped ourselves to the clean ones provided at the pool entrance. A problem did arise when we ran out of toilet tissue. A call to the extremely hard-to-reach front desk yielded no results for toilet paper nearly an hour after our request. I went to the front desk and asked for some and they said they couldn't get it - that housekeeping would be bringing it up. By this time, I had had it. I was in the city to enjoy myself, not to trifle with hotel staff. After some not-so-nice conversation between the front desk clerk and I, the toilet paper was delivered to our room - quite rudely I might add. Day Three: I was glad to be leaving this dump. We requested that the vehicle be brought around about an hour before we were scheduled to leave (by this time we had learned to request it early) When we got downstairs our vehicle was parked in front with no key. They could not find they key, and concluded that another staff member must have it, and he would be back later. When questioned how much later, no one could tell us. An hour later this guy arrives with the key. Unbelievable. Besides the rudeness of basically everyone and the deplorable condition of the suite, there was the noise factor. Our balcony was half a block from Bourbon. It was nice to be in the mix, and the location was convenient, but each night (or morning between 3 and 4 a.m.) we were awakened by people yelling or arguing LOUDLY on Orleans. My personal fave was the 15 minute obscenity fest between what appeared to be a prostitute and her pimp. While this is not the fault of the hotel, anyone wishing to sleep at some point should choose another hotel for this reason alone. How anyone could recommend this place is beyond me. It's a bait and switch. The website touts this luxurious hotel with the fab lobby...(the lobby is pretty but you don't STAY in the lobby) You get here and it's a total let down complete with unbelievably rude and incompetent staff. Bottom line - DO NOT STAY HERE!! 
