<Content>Ok to crash out in, not great for a vacation My boyfriend and I stayed at the Bourbon Orleans this past weekend after celebrating his birthday. Given the fact that we didn't actually check in to the hotel until 5am (woops!) everything was mostly decent, though there are a few things we thought we should point out. We had a slight hassle with the girl at the front desk when we (finally) arrived. We asked to check in, letting her know that we had called about an hour earlier and were assured that our reservation was guaranteed. She gave us a hard time saying things like no, it's not guaranteed, I'll have to re-instate it and it's not guaranteed because you guys have been out partying all night. Um, yeah. This is New Orleans. That's beside the point. She was rude and our check in was not as pleasant as you would expect, but nothing we were completely furious about. Our room was very small, but that's typical of this type of New Orleans hotel, it's just to be expected. Regardless, we were so happy to see a bed it didn't really matter. Beds are comfortable, everything in the room was new and functional. We didn't have much of a view, but we didn't really need one. I'd suggest specifically requesting a view if you're going to be staying for more than one night. In the morning we called for room service. The guy taking the order was a little rude, spoke fast and when he repeated my order to me it was wrong, so I had to repeat it to him again and then he repeated it back to me (correctly, thankfully) and hung up without a response. An hour later, it still wasn't in our room (and it was nearing check out time) so my boyfriend called to make sure they had it. The room service guy abruptly cut him off saying yeah, yeah, continental breakfast in room 449 it's coming right up then hung up. Problem was, we were in room 459, so we had to call back. This time the guy let someone else answer the phone! It was definitely a hassle just to get some pastries and some strawberries delivered to the room. They didn't send any coffee (that's supposed to come with it) but we paid full price for it, and the coffee maker in the room had leftover water and nastiness from the last occupant. None of these things were terribly important to us, considering we were only in the room for about 6 hours, but might be something to think about if you're planning to stay for a vacation. In the morning, I told the front desk girl that we were slightly unsatisfied with our stay, and she gave us 10% off the rate, so no harm done. All in all, the hotel is very pretty (nice lobby area) and has a lot of ammenities on site. We were thankful for a bed, but we probably will not be staying at the Bourbon Orleans again. 
